For the test project configuration, I'll enable `GenerateAssemblyInfo` since there's no conflict. Now I'm planning out the test cases for the NotificationService, mapping out scenarios for different notification types and verifying that messages are created correctly with the right metadata.

I'm also laying out tests for the queue behavior—checking that notifications are received in order, handling capacity limits, and ensuring the read-marking and disposal methods work without errors. Then I'm moving on to the PaginatedList tests, which cover the constructor initialization and the pagination logic for checking previous and next page availability.

Now I'm looking at tests for the Create method to ensure it returns the correct page with proper item assignment and accurate total page calculations. I'm also covering the model tests for full name formatting across Student and Instructor classes, plus the ErrorViewModel's request ID visibility logic. Finally, I'm checking the StudentsController tests for index operations—filtering by search string, sorting by name and date in both directions.

Continuing with the controller tests, I'm verifying the sort defaults to last name, that new searches reset pagination, and then moving through the Details, Create, Edit, and Delete action methods to ensure they handle null IDs, invalid data, and valid requests appropriately. Continuing through the remaining test cases for the Courses controller, then moving into the Departments controller tests which follow a similar pattern of validating null IDs, handling not found scenarios, and testing CRUD operations. Finishing up the test cases for the remaining controllers—HomeController and NotificationsController have their basic coverage mapped out. I'm ready to generate all the test files now.

